'''Racism in South Africa''' can be traced back to the earliest historical accounts of interactions between African, Asian, and European peoples along the coast of [[Southern Africa]].<ref name="Houston 2022">{{cite book |author-last=Houston |author-first=Gregory |year=2022 |chapter=Racial Privilege in Apartheid South Africa |editor1-last=Houston |editor1-first=Gregory |editor2-last=Kanyane |editor2-first=Modimowabarwa |editor3-last=Davids |editor3-first=Yul Derek |title=Paradise Lost: Race and Racism in Post-apartheid South Africa |location=[[Leiden]] and [[Boston]] |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |series=Africa-Europe Group for Interdisciplinary Studies |volume=28 |pages=35–72 |doi=10.1163/9789004515949_003 |isbn=978-90-04-51594-9 |issn=1574-6925}}</ref><ref name="NBK25536">{{cite book |author1-last=Bradshaw |author1-first=Debbie |author2-last=Norman |author2-first=Rosana |author3-last=Laubscher |author3-first=Ria |author4-last=Schneider |author4-first=Michelle |author5-last=Mbananga |author5-first=Nolwazi |author6-last=Steyn |author6-first=Krisela |year=2004 |chapter=Chapter 19: An Exploratory Investigation into Racial Disparities in the Health of Older South Africans |editor1-last=Anderson |editor1-first=N. B. |editor2-last=Bulatao |editor2-first=R. A. |editor3-last=Cohen |editor3-first=B. |title=Critical Perspectives on Racial and Ethnic Differences in Health in Late Life |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |publisher=[[National Academies Press]] on behalf of the National Research Council Panel on Race, Ethnicity, and Health in Later Life |pages=703–736 |doi=10.17226/11086 |pmid=20669464 |id=NBK25536 |isbn=978-0-309-16570-9}}</ref> It has existed throughout several centuries of the [[history of South Africa]],<ref name="Houston 2022"/><ref name="NBK25536"/> dating back to the [[Dutch colonial empire#Dutch colonisation of Southern Africa|Dutch colonization of Southern Africa]], which started in 1652.<ref name="Houston 2022"/><ref name="NBK25536"/> Before universal suffrage was achieved in 1994, [[White South Africans]], especially [[Afrikaners]] during the period of [[Apartheid]], enjoyed various [[Social privilege|legally or socially sanctioned privileges and rights]] that were denied to the indigenous African peoples.<ref name="Houston 2022"/><ref name="NBK25536"/><ref name="bbc.com/news 2021">{{cite news |author=<!--not stated--> |date=21 January 2021 |title=Race in South Africa: 'We haven't learnt we are human beings first' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-55333625 |url-status=live |work=[[BBC News]] |location=[[London]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105115132/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-55333625 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |access-date=10 November 2022}}</ref> Examples of systematic racism over the course of South Africa's history include forced removals, [[racial inequality]] and [[Racial segregation|segregation]], [[Economic inequality|uneven resource distribution]], and [[disenfranchisement]].<ref name="NBK25536"/><ref name="bbc.com/news 2021"/> Racial controversies and politics remain major phenomena in the country.<ref name="NBK25536"/><ref name="bbc.com/news 2021"/><ref name="IMISCOE 2022">{{cite book |author-last=Kaziboni |author-first=Anthony |year=2022 |chapter=Apartheid Racism and Post-apartheid Xenophobia: Bridging the Gap |editor1-last=Rugunanan |editor1-first=Pragna |editor2-last=Xulu-Gama |editor2-first=Nomkhosi |title=Migration in Southern Africa: IMISCOE Regional Reader |location=[[Cham, Switzerland]] |publisher=[[Springer Nature]] |series=IMISCOE Research Series |pages=201–213 |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-92114-9_14 |doi-access=free |isbn=978-3-030-92114-9 |issn=2364-4095}}</ref>

==Colonial racism==
{{Main|History of South Africa}}
{{Further|Dutch Empire#Southern Africa}}

The region that would become modern-day [[South Africa]] was located in a position of advantage for European merchants who were seeking to organize and carry out trade in the [[East Indies]], primarily [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese]] and [[Dutch Empire|Dutch]] colonists.<ref name="Houston 2022"/> In 1652, the [[Dutch East India Company]] founded the [[Dutch Cape Colony|Cape Colony]] at the [[Cape of Good Hope]].<ref name="Houston 2022"/> The purpose of the colony was to ensure that Dutch ships sailing to and from [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] would have a source of fresh provisions, as death by starvation claimed a large number of passengers. During the period of Dutch rule, [[Dutch people|Dutch]] settlers (eventually known as [[Boers]]) began to migrate to the colony, instituting settlements throughout the region.<ref name="Houston 2022"/><ref name="NBK25536"/><ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/South-Africa|title=South Africa - Growth of the colonial economy|website=Britannica.com|date=25 June 2023 }}</ref><ref name="auto1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/article/history-slavery-and-early-colonisation-south-africa|title=History of slavery and early colonisation in South Africa &#124; South African History Online|website=www.sahistory.org.za}}</ref>

The region attracted Dutch [[History of slavery|slave traders]], who imported slaves for wheat farming and viticulture to serve the various Dutch settlements.<ref name="Houston 2022"/><ref name="NBK25536"/> Many slaves escaped their masters by fleeing inland and joining existing groups such as the [[Xhosa people|Xhosa]] or forming groups that were headed by warlords such as those of the Bloem, Kok, and Barends families. By the late 18th century, Arabs and European merchants traded beads, brass, cloth, alcohol, and firearms in exchange for slaves, ivory, gold, wax, cattle, and skins. The profits from these trades encouraged the warlords to hunt elephants and slaves by raiding local communities such as Rolong, Tlhaping, Huruthshe, and Ngwaketse. During the [[Mfecane]], the [[Zulu Kingdom|Zulu]] under [[Shaka]] overran many smaller tribes and enslaved them.<ref name="auto"/>

Many [[Indian people|Indians]] were brought to the colony as slaves. The practice of importing slaves from India stretches back to the 1600s, when the Dutch bought non-Muslim slaves from various kingdoms of India that were ruled by Muslims. By the early part of the 18th century, 80% of the slaves were South Asians, who were not just from the [[Indian subcontinent]] but also those South Asians who were living in south-east Asian regions such as [[Java]]. A slave-trading station was established in [[Maputo|Delagoa Bay]] (present-day Maputo) in 1721 but was abandoned in 1731. Between 1731 and 1765, many Madagascan slaves were bought from [[Madagascar]].<ref name="auto1"/>

The Dutch colonial law defined slaves as property that could be traded, bought, and sold, a form of slavery known as '[[Slavery|chattel slavery]]'. There are many examples of discriminatory practices toward slaves during the colonial period, such as whipping, starvation, being forced to work for long hours, laborers having to carry passes, being subject to high taxation, not being able to walk on the sidewalks, and being banned from living, entering, or working in certain areas, such as the Orange Free State.<ref name="auto1"/> Other examples include the allocation of rations during the [[Siege of Ladysmith]].

{{blockquote|
For Whites—Biscuit, 1/4 lb.; Maize meal, 3 oz.<br/>
For Indians and Kaffirs—Maize meal, 8 oz.<br/>
